Certainly! Below is a Java console application that uses a loop structure to generate the lyrics of the English alphabet song, from "A" to "Z". The code is written following Java programming best practices and proper formatting standards.

```java
public class AlphabetSong {

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Call the method to print the alphabet song
        printAlphabetSong();
    }

    /**
     * Method to print the lyrics of the alphabet song from A to Z.
     */
    private static void printAlphabetSong() {
        // Loop through the ASCII values of uppercase letters A to Z
        for (char letter = 'A'; letter <= 'Z'; letter++) {
            // Print each letter followed by a space
            System.out.print(letter + " ");
        }
        // Print the final line of the song
        System.out.println("\nNow I know my ABCs, next time won't you sing with me?");
    }
}
```

### Explanation:
- The `main` method is the entry point of the Java application. It calls the `printAlphabetSong` method.
- The `printAlphabetSong` method contains a `for` loop that iterates through the ASCII values of the uppercase letters from 'A' to 'Z'.
- Each letter is printed followed by a space to separate them.
- After printing all the letters, a concluding line of the song is printed.
- The use of `System.out.print` within the loop ensures that all letters appear on the same line, and `System.out.println` is used to move to the next line for the final sentence.

This code will display the complete lyrics of the alphabet song on the console, with each letter separated by a space and the final line appearing on a new line.
